 interest groups. Analyzing the negotiation of the original 1995 EU Data Protection Directive, the 2000 Safe Harbor Agreement, and the 2004 Passenger Name Record Agreement, Heisenberg shows that the degree to which business vs. consumer interests were factored into governments' positions was the source not only of U.S.-EU conflicts, but also of their resolution. She finds, too, that public opinion in Europe and the U.S. has been remarkably similar--and thus cannot account for official U.S. reaction to the issues raised by the EU privacy directive. More broadly, Negotiating Privacy sheds important light on both the relationship between the U.S. and the EU and the relationship between domestic issues and the development of international rules.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationxEuropean Union countries. 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationzEuropean Union countries. 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxEuropean Union countries. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxUnited StatesxEuropexEuropean Union countriesxUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzEuropean Union countries. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 0aRecordsxLaw and legislationxEuropean Union countries. 0aRecordsxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aRecordsxLaw and legislationzEuropean Union countries. 0aRecordsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / European.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078425140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637007440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626370074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626370074/original  a978-3-11-078425-1  Lynne Rienner Pres